Lille Richd Southell
Sr. I have duely recd. yd of 23.th pass. for want of occasion die not answer
itt sooner I do not know what m. van Ess might have told you butt I can
testifie with 2 withness that he him leffr brought. yd bill &ached fitt
was good: Itold him that no advise from you, though I was ready to accept
itt, he replyed that he was not in laste for itt, & there fore could keep it
3 or 4 dayes which I die, which time beeng exspired & haveing no advises
from you have accepted itt & delivered him my self, without he asked
ofor itt att all, so that you have no obligation to him for thouse things
happen vere often & Itinck I did not in the least where in you can
blame mee I want y yard of black flanders lace about ⅓ of advtis
all broad or better which I knowing is made att lille so desire you to send
itt mee pr. first of an indifferent sort so tis to be sent to greland
I am ghad our bale N.10 is arrivee here is notking to doi no trade nor
proffist yett vale att Brussels hath a quick trade & sells a woldof
goods there & sy suplyes them, so that I can not come there any more
I can not yett my mony of thomas seamad for stuffs he sold
for W.B & is about £40 p. Ballance & he knows no better
butt that they be yours, so you will oblige mee to write to him
& desiriny to make on end to that stuff bussines for Hold him
you that they oy bo yours to you had been verenrgent
there noto of late there fore leet mee in treat you towrise
him a letter under mij covert: for I doubt he will forls him self
bij beeng so much a gentman, as he is keephorse & serwant

In Antwerp 6 augusti 1681
London Henry marnard
S. my last to you was on the 30 past. sence non from you I have been att Brussel
where I did not receane the exspected mony neither have I sold any thing considerable there
as formerly I have don often, though they have there agreat demand & itt seems & T
is the onely man now that can sell his goods, they beeng alwayes sold att arrivall
whoever I can butt do my indeavour, here ist is not quick yett butt vere dead
though wee now dayly exspect a good sale towards which the good abbatt pindar
come vere seasourdlij) for he is( god betancked, well arrivde in closed remitt
you ƒ592:7 att 52: which I make £128„ 6:7 st though there is less noted
up on the bill, beeng due the curitt on Jeremias nathaniel & sinon bonnell
for my acctt & £250: att 2 uso on m. William Scawen for yd acctt
att 35:4 ½ for boath please to procure the needfull & note accordingly, I hope
now to continew remise better then of late I have been able to do I hope
mr. Scawen shall be in cash for mye to pay you £100: or some what more
for my acctt. for I want itt by you there fore I hope he will not take itt
ill in case you ashe him I have no news yett of klarck or barbar
butt hope they may come safe over: some of my custumers att Brussels
that have seen the fine spanish cloathes which I receaved of late
have desired mee to in order 8 a 10 paurts supra fine peeces of the mwest
mode that is att paris & bestow from so to 14 s ayd butt as to the
cullours I know not which the draps. are not much demanded in suprad
fine ggoods I have the last patt. you sent mee, & yett know nott which
to venter so pray endeavour all you can to provide this tryall & do yd ut
most to gest some thing perticulars, for I never had yett any supra fine
from you & those JV last receaved are all sold & pleased his custunners
as I understood, so you know best what itt was, itt vere 2 bales besides you
know what is att Lille & paris demanded so leaved itt to you onely avoid
extrauagant light cullours inclosed a letter to m. slaughter which please
to deliveer him whirst I remaine with kinde saito
@ 6 August
London paris slaughter
Sr. I have he therto don all I could to make mony of the effect of the
peeters boath of standing out debts & goods in sold some of them
are sold butt vere few, so that thereis yett 18 yr. resting & I will no
longer be with nt even acctt. whith them there fore must intreat
you to order mee to to send to you these goods up on condition that you
shall sell them & the proceed allow up on their acctts & I shall remitt you
as soone as you consent this so much as there is in cash, I thuck
you can not loose for though the cloathes should yeald £50:-:
less then their cost yett have the rest here in mony & standing out
debto I have the 2 bills rectosthe charges theires of mad Bouwens which
I keep to yd order the charges shall pay to them here so pray make
an end to that bassynes that I be dischargee for assolute y the cloates
enot tobe sald here & so remane
